<span id="freeTextContainer16882048754706483315">In the Deep South of the 1950s, journalist <i>John Howard Griffin</i> decided to cross the color line. Using medication that darkened his skin to deep brown, he exchanged his privileged life as a Southern white man for the disenfranchised world of an unemployed black man. His audacious, still chillingly relevant eyewitness history is a work about race and humanity-that in this ne</span>
  <span id="freeText16882048754706483315" style="display:none">In the Deep South of the 1950s, journalist <i>John Howard Griffin</i> decided to cross the color line. Using medication that darkened his skin to deep brown, he exchanged his privileged life as a Southern white man for the disenfranchised world of an unemployed black man. His audacious, still chillingly relevant eyewitness history is a work about race and humanity-that in this new millennium still has something important to say to every American.</span>
